---
title: Sizzling Sesame Korean Beef with Bok Choy
description: In his tireless quest for new recipe inspiration Patrick has been eating at a few Korean restaurants of late and was inspired to knock up this sizzling beef number. The trick is to put your steak in the freezer for 40 minutes before you start and then it’s easier to slice wafer thin ribbons for a deliciously tender finish!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/54cf8dc36ced6e7d788b4567.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/54cf8dc36ced6e7d788b4567.pdf
nutrition:
  calories: 520 kcal
  fat: 18 g
  saturated fat: 5 g
  carbohydrates: 40 g
  protein: 47 g
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
time required: 40 minutes
course: main course
cuisine: Asian
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/sizzling-sesame-korean-beef-54cf8dc36ced6e7d788b4567
---

Put your @Roaming Roosters Steak{1} in the #freezer{} for ~{40%minutes} before you
start cooking (essential step!). Peel and finely dice the @garlic{1/2%clove}. Peel
the @ginger{2/3%inch piece} using the edge of a #spoon{} and very finely chop (or
grate). Chop the @spring onion{2} into micro-thin discs, separating the white and
green parts.

Mix together the @Chinese soy sauce{3%tbsp} with @sugar{1%tbsp} and the
@sesame oil{1/2%tbsp}. Add the ginger and garlic and keep stirring until the sugar
dissolves. Next stir in the whites of the spring onions.

Slice the beef into as many wafer thin slices as you can. Add the beef to the soy
sauce mixture, stir thoroughly and leave for as long as possible.

> This would be a great step to do well in advance - we left it for an hour and it
> made a HUGE difference to the flavour, but let your appetite make the decision!

Bring @water{300%ml} to a gentle boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} in a medium sized
#pot{}. Place your @basmati rice{200%g} into the boiling water and put on a
#lid{}. Cook for ~{10%minutes} on the lowest heat possible then remove from the
heat for ~{10%minutes}. Do not touch the lid until 20 mins are up to ensure the
rice is cooked perfectly.

Boil 3cm of water in another medium sized pot and place a #colander{} over the
top.

> The bottom of the colander should not touch the water.

Very finely chop ('shred') the @pak choi{1} widthways and place in the colander.
Put a lid on top and steam the bok choy for ~{2%minutes} before keeping to the side.

Heat a teaspoon of @oil{1%tsp} on high heat in a #frying pan{}. Once really hot
add a cupful of your beef mix and fry for around ~{4-5%minutes} until cooked.

> Patrick slightly undercooked his to keep it really juicy.

> Cooking in batches will stop the meat stewing and give you a nicer texture.

Separate the grains of rice with a #fork{} and stir through the greens of the
spring onion. Stir through the bok choy and serve your beef on top with a sprinkle
of @sesame seeds{2}.